snippet.textDisplay: Go look at fighter reactions to close decisions and you will see why what they are saying is bullshit. I respect them both, but the evidence says otherwise. Every time there is a close decision, professional fighters are usually split with their opinions on it, favouring the style the personally like over the judging criteria. A guy like Cruz might give someone a win for coming up with more clever entries into striking and takedowns while a guy like Askren will favour control time for example. There is nothing wrong with pro fighters judging fights, but they need to be taught the impartial criteria properly, and stick to it. And even then, MMA judging is hard as shit, sometimes the fight should really just be a draw, but judges are forced to give someone the win so ppl get pissed
snippet.textOriginal: Go look at fighter reactions to close decisions and you will see why what they are saying is bullshit. I respect them both, but the evidence says otherwise. Every time there is a close decision, professional fighters are usually split with their opinions on it, favouring the style the personally like over the judging criteria. A guy like Cruz might give someone a win for coming up with more clever entries into striking and takedowns while a guy like Askren will favour control time for example. There is nothing wrong with pro fighters judging fights, but they need to be taught the impartial criteria properly, and stick to it. And even then, MMA judging is hard as shit, sometimes the fight should really just be a draw, but judges are forced to give someone the win so ppl get pissed
